In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
    }

    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = new Window(new AppShell());

        window.Created   += (s, e) => Log("Created");
        window.Activated  += (s, e) => Log("Activated");
        window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Log("Deactivated");
        window.Stopped    += (s, e) => Log("Stopped");
        window.Resumed    += (s, e) => Log("Resumed");
        window.Destroying += (s, e) => Log("Destroying");
        // Display-related
        window.SizeChanged      += (s, e) => Log($"SizeChanged: {window.Width}x{window.Height}");
        window.Backgrounding    += (s, e) => Log("Backgrounding");
        window.DisplayDensityChanged += (s, e) => Log($"DisplayDensityChanged: {e.DisplayDensity}");

        return window;
    }

    static void Log(string transition)
        => System.Diagnostics.Debug.WriteLine($"[Window] {DateTime.Now:HH:mm:ss.fff} — {transition}");
}
```

**Typical lifecycle order:**

| Transition | When |
|---|---|
| `Created` | Window is first created |
| `Activated` | Window receives focus |
| `Deactivated` | Window loses focus |
| `Stopped` | Window is no longer visible |
| `Resumed` | Window returns from stopped state |
| `Backgrounding` | *(iOS/Mac Catalyst only)* App is backgrounding — save state here |
| `Destroying` | Window is being torn down |

> **Tip:** On Android/iOS, minimizing triggers `Deactivated → Stopped`, and restoring triggers `Resumed → Activated`. Use the `Debug` output window in Visual Studio to watch the log in real time.
